# Day 91 – Capstone Part 5: Policies and Procedures | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## The Governance Layer That Makes Controls Sustainable

Day 90 produced the control implementation plan — risk-to-control traceability showing that the OpenMRS technical controls are largely effective, with three meaningful gaps: the phishing simulation absence (human layer effectiveness undemonstrated), the AU-12 denied-access logging gap (detection capability reduced), and the CP-2 AT RISK condition (clinical downtime procedures not yet complete). The control section also identified a policy architecture gap: several policies referenced in the SSP have never been developed as standalone organizational documents with owners, acknowledgment requirements, and review cycles.

Day 91 addresses that gap directly. But I want to be honest about what "policies and procedures" means at the capstone stage of a program that has been running for eight months, because the framing matters for how this section is read.

At initial GRC program design, the policy section answers "what policies do we need?" At the capstone stage, the policy section answers two different questions: "which policies are fully developed and operational?" and "which policies exist only as SSP references or partial documents, and what is the plan to complete them?" The honest answer to both questions tells a more useful story than presenting a policy list as though every item were equally complete.

The OpenMRS program has one fully developed standalone policy (IS-AC-001 Access Control Policy), one operational plan document (the Incident Response Plan), one plan document in development under an authorization condition (CP-2 Contingency Plan), and a set of policy needs that have been documented in the SSP but never formalized as organizational governance documents. This section organizes that complete picture.

