## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-12 Rev 1 describes the policy development framework — the hierarchy from organizational policy through system-specific policy through procedures and guidelines. The Day 76 policy writing section established the policy hierarchy (policy → standard → procedure → guideline) and identified the five writing failure modes (passive voice, "should" instead of "must," scope ambiguity, missing exception process, no enforcement reference). Today I apply that framework to the complete OpenMRS policy inventory — documenting current status for existing policies and drafting the substance for the two highest-priority new documents.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified the policy section today is understanding that a policy without an acknowledgment requirement is not an enforceable policy.

IS-AC-001, the Access Control Policy developed in Day 76, contains specific obligations — "Users must not share account credentials under any circumstances" (Section 3.1), "All user sessions must timeout after 15 minutes of inactivity" (Section 3.4). These are written in the mandatory voice with named enforcement references. But the policy's enforceability depends on users having been formally presented with the policy and acknowledged their obligation to comply. Without that acknowledgment, the organization's ability to take disciplinary action for a policy violation is weaker — the user can plausibly claim they were unaware of the requirement.

This is especially significant for the Acceptable Use Policy gap identified in Day 90. RS-005 (insider misuse) is one of the program's Moderate residual risks. The primary deterrence mechanism for insider misuse — beyond access controls and audit logging — is the credible organizational consequence for misuse. That consequence depends on a policy that was formally communicated and acknowledged. A clinician who accesses a patient record without clinical justification has violated HIPAA and the Access Control Policy, but if there is no signed AUP establishing that they understood their obligations, the disciplinary response is harder to execute cleanly.

This is why the AUP is not just a nice-to-have second-year priority — it is a material gap in the insider threat deterrence architecture.

