## The Policy Governance Lifecycle — What This Program Has Learned

The policy governance lifecycle has three phases that the Day 76 analysis identified: writing, communication/training, and monitoring. Eight months of operations have produced lessons about each:

**Writing:** The IS-AC-001 policy development process — starting from organizational specificity (this system, these roles, this enforcement mechanism) rather than adapting a generic template — produced a policy that maps directly to the system's actual operation. The policy writing failures (passive voice, "should" instead of "must," scope ambiguity) are real failure modes that generic templates often exhibit. The second-year policies should follow the same specificity-first approach.

**Communication and training:** The IT Administrator's CM-3 compliance pattern (M-002, A-7) suggests that communication of the change management procedure was not sufficient to produce consistent behavioral compliance. Communication of a policy is not the same as acknowledgment of a policy obligation. The change management policy development for year two should include an explicit acknowledgment step — the IT Administrator signs that they have read and understood the change management requirements — so that subsequent compliance conversations have a clear reference point.

**Monitoring:** The quarterly access review (AC-2) is a policy monitoring mechanism — it confirms that the Access Control Policy's role-based access requirements are being maintained. The M-004 finding (one over-privilege instance corrected in Q1) demonstrates the monitoring mechanism working as designed. For the second-year policies (AUP, change management, vendor management), equivalent monitoring mechanisms need to be defined at policy development time, not added later.

