## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The importance of the Acceptable Use Policy as a deterrence mechanism — not just a compliance document — is illustrated by the **2017 Memorial Healthcare System settlement ($5.5 million, one of the largest HIPAA settlements at the time)**.

The OCR investigation found that a workforce member had used login credentials of a former employee to access ePHI without authorization over a period of approximately a year. The access control failure was real — the former employee's credentials had not been promptly deprovisioned (an AC-2 issue). But the investigation also identified that the workforce member who used those credentials had not been formally presented with a policy that clearly prohibited this behavior and defined the consequences.

The Memorial Healthcare case is directly relevant to the OpenMRS AUP gap because it shows that technical access control failures (delayed deprovisioning) are more likely to be exploited when the workforce has not been formally presented with a policy that establishes clear behavioral expectations and consequences. The IS-AC-001 policy covers deprovisioning timing. The missing AUP covers the workforce member's obligation not to use credentials they are not authorized to use — and the consequences if they do.

The combined lesson: technical controls (AC-2 deprovisioning) and administrative controls (AUP establishing behavioral obligations) work together. Either one alone leaves a gap that the other cannot fully compensate for.

